/* ============================================================
   PASSAGE 1 — THE OCTOPUS
   ============================================================ */
const P_OCTOPUS = { title:`The Octopus: Master of Camouflage and Intelligence`, html:`<p><b>A.</b> Hidden among the rocks and coral of the world's oceans lives one of nature's most remarkable creatures: the octopus. With eight long arms, three hearts, and blue blood, the octopus is unlike any other animal on Earth. These soft-bodied creatures have captured human curiosity for centuries due to their extraordinary abilities and apparent intelligence. Despite having no bones, they can squeeze through impossibly small openings, escape from secure containers, and even open jars to retrieve food inside.</p><p><b>B.</b> Perhaps the octopus's most impressive feature is its ability to change colour and texture almost instantly. Special cells in its skin called chromatophores contain pigment that can expand or contract, allowing the octopus to match its surroundings perfectly. Some species can also alter the texture of their skin to mimic rough coral or smooth sand. This remarkable camouflage helps the octopus hide from predators such as sharks and large fish, and also allows it to ambush prey without being detected.</p><p><b>C.</b> Beyond their physical abilities, octopuses demonstrate surprising intelligence. They have been observed using tools, such as collecting coconut shells to build mobile shelters. In laboratory experiments, they have learned to navigate mazes, solve puzzles, and recognize individual human faces. Some scientists believe octopuses may possess a form of consciousness, although this remains debated. Their large brains relative to body size place them among the most intelligent invertebrates known to science.</p><p><b>D.</b> Hunting is where the octopus's combination of stealth and intelligence truly shines. Most species are opportunistic hunters, feeding on crabs, shrimp, fish, and even other octopuses. They use their flexible arms to explore crevices and capture prey. The suction cups on each arm contain taste receptors, allowing the octopus to "taste" what it touches. Once caught, prey is paralyzed by a venom the octopus injects through its sharp beak, making it easier to consume.</p><p><b>E.</b> Sadly, octopus populations face increasing threats from human activity. Climate change is warming ocean waters and increasing acidity, which affects their food supply and reproduction. Overfishing has also reduced their numbers in some regions. Marine biologists are working to better understand octopus behavior and habitat needs, hoping to inform conservation efforts. With proper protection, these intelligent and mysterious creatures can continue to amaze us for generations to come.</p>` };

