/* ============================================================
   PASSAGE 2 — CORAL REEFS
   ============================================================ */
const P_CORAL = { title:`Coral Reefs: The Rainforests of the Sea`, html:`<p><b>A.</b> Coral reefs are often called the rainforests of the sea, and for good reason. Although they cover less than one per cent of the ocean floor, they are home to about a quarter of all marine species. A reef may look like a colourful rocky garden, but it is actually built by millions of tiny living animals called coral polyps. Each polyp is no bigger than a grain of rice, yet together they create structures so large that some can be seen from space.</p><p><b>B.</b> A coral polyp has a soft body and a hard outer skeleton made of limestone. As old polyps die, new ones grow on top of the old skeletons, slowly building the reef over thousands of years. Inside the tissue of each polyp live tiny algae called zooxanthellae. These algae use sunlight to make food through photosynthesis, and they share this food with the coral. In return, the coral gives the algae a safe, sunlit home. This close partnership benefits both partners.</p><p><b>C.</b> Coral reefs provide enormous value to both nature and people. They act as natural barriers that protect coastlines from powerful storm waves, reducing damage to towns and villages. They support fishing industries that feed millions of people, and they attract tourists whose spending helps coastal economies. Scientists also study reef organisms in the hope of discovering new medicines for human diseases.</p><p><b>D.</b> Unfortunately, reefs around the world are in serious danger. When the sea becomes too warm, stressed corals expel the colourful algae living inside them. The coral turns pale and white, a process known as coral bleaching. A bleached coral is not yet dead, but if the warm conditions continue, it will starve and die. Pollution, careless tourism, and destructive fishing methods cause further harm to these fragile ecosystems.</p><p><b>E.</b> Protecting coral reefs requires action at every level. Governments can create marine protected areas where fishing and building are limited. Reducing greenhouse gas emissions would help slow the warming of the oceans. Ordinary people can help too, by avoiding products that damage reefs and by supporting responsible tourism. With careful management, these underwater wonders may survive for future generations to admire.</p>` };

