/* ============================================================
   PASSAGE 3 — THE SAHARA DESERT
   ============================================================ */
const P_SAHARA = { title:`The Sahara: Life in the World's Largest Hot Desert`, html:`<p><b>A.</b> Stretching across northern Africa, the Sahara is the largest hot desert on Earth, covering an area almost as big as the United States. It is a land of extremes. During the day, the temperature can climb above 50 degrees Celsius, while at night it may fall close to freezing. Rain is rare, and in some parts of the desert it has not rained for years. To many people, the Sahara seems like an empty and lifeless place.</p><p><b>B.</b> Yet the Sahara is far from lifeless. A surprising number of plants and animals have adapted to survive its harsh conditions. The fennec fox, with its enormous ears, releases body heat through them to stay cool. Many desert animals are nocturnal, meaning they rest in burrows during the burning day and become active only after sunset. Plants such as the date palm send roots deep underground to reach hidden water.</p><p><b>C.</b> Humans have lived in and around the Sahara for thousands of years. The Tuareg people, sometimes called the "blue people" because of their indigo-dyed clothing, have crossed the desert for centuries leading camel caravans. They know how to find water at hidden wells and oases, where underground water reaches the surface and allows trees and crops to grow. These green islands have always been vital stopping points for desert travellers.</p><p><b>D.</b> The Sahara has not always been a desert. Thousands of years ago, the region was much greener, with lakes, rivers, and grasslands where elephants and hippos once lived. Ancient rock paintings found deep in the desert show people swimming and herding cattle. Slow changes in the Earth's climate gradually dried the land, turning a green landscape into the vast desert we see today.</p><p><b>E.</b> Today the Sahara faces new challenges and opportunities. The desert is slowly spreading into nearby farmland, a process called desertification that threatens the livelihoods of millions. At the same time, scientists see great promise in the desert's endless sunshine. Large solar power projects could one day turn the Sahara's fierce sunlight into clean electricity for many countries.</p>` };

