/* ============================================================
   PASSAGE 4 — HONEYBEES
   ============================================================ */
const P_BEES = { title:`Honeybees: Small Insects, Big Importance`, html:`<p><b>A.</b> Honeybees are among the most useful insects on the planet. Although a single bee is small enough to sit on a fingertip, the work of bees affects the food on tables all around the world. As bees move from flower to flower collecting nectar, they carry pollen with them. This process, known as pollination, allows plants to produce seeds and fruit. Without it, many of the foods that people enjoy would become rare or disappear completely.</p><p><b>B.</b> A honeybee colony is a marvel of teamwork and organisation. A single hive may contain tens of thousands of bees, and each bee has a clear role. The queen is the only female that lays eggs, sometimes more than a thousand in a single day. Male bees, called drones, exist mainly to mate with a new queen. The vast majority of the colony are worker bees, all female, which clean the hive, feed the young, build the wax cells, and gather food.</p><p><b>C.</b> One of the most fascinating things about honeybees is how they communicate. When a worker bee finds a rich source of food, it returns to the hive and performs a special movement known as the "waggle dance". The direction and length of the dance tell the other bees exactly where the flowers are and how far away they lie. In this clever way, information about food is shared quickly across the whole colony.</p><p><b>D.</b> Bees also help humans directly by producing honey and beeswax. Bees make honey by collecting nectar and storing it in the hive, where it slowly thickens into a sweet, energy-rich food. People have valued honey for thousands of years, both as a food and as a natural medicine. Beeswax, produced by worker bees, has long been used to make candles, polish, and cosmetics.</p><p><b>E.</b> Sadly, honeybee numbers have been falling in many countries. Scientists believe several causes are to blame, including the loss of wild flowers, the use of harmful chemicals on crops, diseases, and pests such as tiny mites. Because bees are so important to agriculture, protecting them is essential. Planting flowers, reducing pesticide use, and supporting local beekeepers are simple steps that can make a real difference.</p>` };

