/* ============================================================
   PASSAGE 9 — THE WATER CYCLE
   ============================================================ */
const P_WATER = { title:`The Water Cycle: Nature's Endless Journey`, html:`<p><b>A.</b> Water is one of the most important substances on Earth, and no living thing can survive without it. What many people do not realise is that the amount of water on our planet stays almost the same. The very same water has been moving around the Earth for millions of years, travelling between the oceans, the air, and the land in a continuous process known as the water cycle.</p><p><b>B.</b> The journey begins when heat from the Sun warms the surface of seas, lakes, and rivers. This causes liquid water to change into an invisible gas called water vapour, a process called evaporation. Plants add to this moisture too. Through tiny holes in their leaves, they release water vapour into the air in a process known as transpiration.</p><p><b>C.</b> As warm, moist air rises high into the sky, it cools down. The cooler air cannot hold as much water vapour, so the vapour changes back into tiny droplets of liquid water. This process is called condensation, and it is how clouds are formed. A single cloud may contain millions of these tiny water droplets floating together in the air.</p><p><b>D.</b> Inside a cloud, the tiny droplets bump into one another and join together. Over time, they grow larger and heavier until the air can no longer hold them up. The water then falls back to the ground as precipitation, which may take the form of rain, snow, or hail depending on the temperature. In this way, water that rose from the oceans returns to the surface of the Earth.</p><p><b>E.</b> Once water reaches the ground, its journey continues. Some of it flows over the land in streams and rivers, eventually returning to the sea. Some soaks down into the soil and is stored underground, where it may remain for a long time. From there, the water will one day evaporate again, and the endless cycle will repeat, just as it has done for countless ages.</p>` };

